\begin_layout Subsection*
Reflection,
 Marshalling,
 and Metaprogramming
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Renaissance era,
 we avoid "Runtime Reflection" because it is a black box that hides errors until the program crashes.
 Instead,
 we use 
\series bold
Derivation
\series default
 and 
\series bold
Macros
\series default
.
 This allows the compiler to look at your classes and write the boring "glue code" for you.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Automatic Marshalling (Type-class Derivation)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marshalling is the process of turning a memory object into a format like JSON or XML.
 In the past,
 this required slow reflection.
 In Scala 3,
 we use the 
\family typewriter
derives
\family default
 keyword.
 The compiler "reflects" on the structure of your class at compile-time and generates the Marshaller automatically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import zio.json.*
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// The 'derives' keyword tells Scala to write the JSON logic for you
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
case class User(name:
 String,
 email:
 String) derives JsonCodec
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val user = User("Alice",
 "alice@startup.io")
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val json = user.toJson // "{"name":"Alice","email":"alice@startup.io"}"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Mirrors:
 The New Reflection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scala 3 introduces 
\family typewriter
Mirror
\family default
.
 A Mirror is a compile-time representation of a class's shape.
 It tells you the names of the fields and their types without ever needing to "instantiate" the class.
 This is how libraries like 
\family typewriter
Doobie
\family default
 map database rows to your Case Classes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
import scala.deriving.Mirror
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// A Mirror lets you inspect Task without using Java Reflection
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val m = summon[Mirror.Of[User]]
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// m.MirroredElemLabels contains ("name",
 "email")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Inlining:
 Reflection without the Cost
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\family typewriter
inline
\family default
 keyword is a request to the compiler to "copy-paste" the code at the call site.
 When combined with 
\family typewriter
if
\family default
 statements,
 the compiler can perform "Constant Folding"—
evaluating logic during compilation and removing dead code.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
inline def log(msg:
 String):
 Unit =
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  inline if Thread.currentThread().getName == "main" then
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
    println(s"[MAIN] $msg")
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// If called outside 'main',
 the compiler removes the entire call!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Macros:
 Inspecting Code as Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While Ruby uses 
\family typewriter
eval
\family default
 to run strings as code,
 Scala 3 uses 
\family typewriter
Quotes
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
Splices
\family default
 (as seen in Chapter 23).
 This is "Safe Reflection." You can inspect the AST (Abstract Syntax Tree) of a piece of code,
 validate it,
 and then transform it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// A macro that prints the name of a variable at compile-time
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
inline def debug(inline expr:
 Any):
 Unit = 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  ${ debugImpl('expr) }
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

